  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3485583072" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3485583072" />
    <a title="Gary Guinn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/62691310-gary-guinn"><img alt="Gary Guinn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1493496456p2/62691310.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3485583072?book_show_action=true">Aug 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gary Guinn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gary Guinn" href="/user/show/62691310-gary-guinn">Gary Guinn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3485583072" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5363395661409093204"><i>Smila’s Sense of Snow</i>, by Peter Hoeg, was published in Danish in 1992 (in English in 1993). I’ve been a fan of Nordic Noir for several years, but somehow missed this one. I’m glad I finally stumbled across it. The main character, Smila, is perhaps the most interesting character I’ve read in a long time. More important than all other characteristics is the fact that she is a Greenlander living in Denmark. Her situation frequently reminded me of the struggle of Native Americans living in white Ame</span>
  <span id="freeText5363395661409093204" style="display:none"><i>Smila’s Sense of Snow</i>, by Peter Hoeg, was published in Danish in 1992 (in English in 1993). I’ve been a fan of Nordic Noir for several years, but somehow missed this one. I’m glad I finally stumbled across it. The main character, Smila, is perhaps the most interesting character I’ve read in a long time. More important than all other characteristics is the fact that she is a Greenlander living in Denmark. Her situation frequently reminded me of the struggle of Native Americans living in white American culture—the same disadvantages, the same prejudices, the same tragic loss of self and place. But Smila is not a victim. She is brilliant and driven. The publisher’s blurb says, “She thinks more highly of snow and ice than she does of love. She lives in a world of numbers, science, and memories—a dark, exotic stranger in a strange land.” As a Greenlander, Smila possesses a variety of words for snow and ice, and at every turn she offers the precise word for it, the word that makes all the difference to human life in the exact situation. There is nothing artificial about this element of her voice. It’s innate and beautiful.<br /><br />The novel is narrated in first person by Smila, and the narrative is driven by the death of a young friend and neighbor, Isaiah, who is also a Greenlander. The death was ruled an accident, but Smila pursues the facts relentlessly until she begins to uncover a much bigger secret. Hoeg’s writing is wonderful, poetic, descriptive. Here’s the opening paragraph of the novel:<br /><blockquote>It’s freezing—an extraordinary 0 degrees Fahrenheit—and it’s snowing, and in the<br />language that is no longer mine, the snow is qanik—big, almost weightless crystals <br />falling in clumps and covering the ground with a layer of pulverized white frost.</blockquote><br /><br />The language, the characters, the events are haunting in this novel. Smila is an engaging combination of strength and vulnerability, sometimes in complete control of events, sometimes hovering on the edge of disaster, but always she is the outsider working to use the system to reach her ends. <br /><br /><i>Smila’s Sense of Snow</i> is a novel I think I’ll read again at some point in the future. It was turned into a film in 1997, so I may watch that too. I can’t quite leave Smila behind.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5363395661409093204" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

