<div id="review_2998583620" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2998583620" />
    <a title="Bob Newman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/72341080-bob-newman"><img alt="Bob Newman" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2998583620?book_show_action=true">Oct 02, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bob Newman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bob Newman" href="/user/show/72341080-bob-newman">Bob Newman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/72341080-bob-newman?shelf=pop-fiction">pop-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2998583620" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2387995221322532936">Smilla’s suspicion starts snowy spiral of slayings<br/><br/>An Inuit kid falls off a snowy roof in Copenhagen. Ah, but was he pushed? He was afraid of heights so he wouldn’t have been up there just fooling around. Smilla, half-Greenlandic Inuit, half-Danish, loved this neighbor kid. She is a crusty loner of 37, who has a scientific background to do with snow and ice, as well as a childhood hunting around northern Greenland with her mum. She determines to find out. She is actually a “Jane Bond”, as you wil</span>
  <span id="freeText2387995221322532936" style="display:none">Smilla’s suspicion starts snowy spiral of slayings<br /><br />An Inuit kid falls off a snowy roof in Copenhagen. Ah, but was he pushed? He was afraid of heights so he wouldn’t have been up there just fooling around. Smilla, half-Greenlandic Inuit, half-Danish, loved this neighbor kid. She is a crusty loner of 37, who has a scientific background to do with snow and ice, as well as a childhood hunting around northern Greenland with her mum. She determines to find out. She is actually a “Jane Bond”, as you will soon realize if you read this thriller totally unrelated to reality. What can I say? I seldom read stuff like this and only finished it from my perverse habit of finishing books I start. Though I admit that certain passages about wind, ice, and snow are beautifully written, the style also may remind you of those old “Perils of Pauline” silent movies where the heroine is miraculously saved every time. They actually did make a film of the book back in 1997 but I haven’t seen it. The dialogues sometimes leave you wondering what they are talking about because they don’t always seem to mesh with the situation. The long, unnecessary section aboard a ship bound on a mysterious mission to the waters off Greenland is replete with sleep-inducing descriptions of the ship in minute detail. Zzzzzzzz. Drug addicts, fires, harpoon gun murders, escape by dumb waiter, a bit of sex, lists of all kinds of gear, fights, recipes, and aliens. This here book has got it all. If you want “it all”. That might be the question. But---I might add---what is missing is an ending. It kind of just shuffles off into the snowy night. <br /> <br /> If you like such books, then I apologize and say that it might be a five-star book for you.<br />Not for me. I bought it at a library sale long ago and just now took it off the shelf. Well, it only cost a dime. It is lively, but not deep. I'm sure the author became quite wealthy off this work, but that doesn't make literature.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2387995221322532936" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


